== 7. d5?! · Richter variation  ==

White leaves their bishop ''en prise'' to counterattack Black's knight instead.  

Black can rescue the knight '''7...Ne7''' and it seems then White must play 8. Bb3 anyway. However, White has the devious move 8. Re1!, where the natural move 8...Nc5?, which preserves the knight and prepares to trade off the bishop, is an error: 9. Nxe5 bxa4?? 10. Qf3! threatens 11. Qxf2#. 10...f6? 11. Qh5+!. 

In actual fact, allowing the trade of knight for bishop (either knight, 7...Ne7 8. Re1 bxa4 or 7...bxa4 8. dxc6) is fine for Black:

After '''7...bxa4''' 8. dxc6 d6, forget about Black's potentially slightly rubbish rook pawns, one of which is an extra pawn anyway. Black has a stable centre, a half-open b-file, a kingside pawn majority that could quite easily wallop White after ...f5 and ...Nf6 and the bishop pair: it's one of those rare positions that are just really good fun (your mileage may vary). 

